WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.560
<v Teacher>The word <i>to give</i> in Spanish is <b>dar</b>. <i>D-a-r</i>, <b>dar</b>.

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:07.440
<v Student><b>Dar</b>.

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:08.160
<v Teacher><b>Dar</b>.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:09.120
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:09.019 --> 00:00:11.340
<v Teacher><i>I give</i> is <b>doy</b>.

00:00:11.340 --> 00:00:13.900
<v Teacher>So it's like <i>boy</i> ending –<i>oy</i>.

00:00:13.900 --> 00:00:14.700
<v Teacher><b>Doy</b>.

00:00:14.700 --> 00:00:15.500
<v Student><b>Doy</b>.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:16.219
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:16.219 --> 00:00:17.980
<v Teacher>I give it.

00:00:18.859 --> 00:00:19.980
<v Student><b>Lo doy</b>.

00:00:19.980 --> 00:00:20.619
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:20.619 --> 00:00:23.340
<v Teacher><i>I give them</i>:

00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:24.380
<v Student><b>Los doy</b>.

00:00:24.380 --> 00:00:24.539
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:24.539 --> 00:00:27.500
<v Teacher>And what if there were feminine things that you were giving?

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:28.860
<v Student><b>Las doy</b>.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:29.099
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:29.099 --> 00:00:30.939
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>he gives</i>?

00:00:30.939 --> 00:00:31.539
<v Student><b>Da</b>.

00:00:31.539 --> 00:00:34.860
<v Teacher><b>Da</b>. <i>He gives</i>, emphasizing <i>he</i>:

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:36.860
<v Student><b>Él da</b>.

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:39.860
<v Teacher><b>Él da</b>. Good. And <i>she gives</i>:

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:41.860
<v Student><b>Ella da</b>.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:44.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:47.560
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>they give</i>?

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:49.480
<v Student><b>Ellos dan</b>.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:49.960
<v Teacher>Good!

00:00:49.960 --> 00:00:51.240
<v Teacher><b>Ellos dan</b>

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:52.920
<v Teacher>or <b>ellas</b> for feminine.

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:54.120
<v Teacher><b>Ellas dan</b>. Good.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.840
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal) <i>give</i>?

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:58.160
<v Student><b>Das</b>.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.160
<v Teacher><b>Das</b>. And if you wanted to emphasize this <i>you</i>?

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:04.439
<v Student><b>Tú das</b>.

00:01:05.479 --> 00:01:05.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:08.680
<v Teacher>The word for <i>something</i> we said was <b>algo</b>.

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:09.399
<v Teacher><b>Algo</b>.

00:01:09.399 --> 00:01:12.119
<v Teacher>So how would you say he's giving me something?

00:01:12.119 --> 00:01:14.520
<v Teacher>He's giving me something.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:18.720
<v Student><b>Él me da algo</b>.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:19.520
<v Teacher>Good!

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:21.280
<v Teacher><b>Él me da algo</b>.

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:23.920
<v Teacher>They give me something.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:27.040
<v Student><b>Me dan algo</b>.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:27.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:29.280
<v Teacher><b>Me dan algo</b>.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:33.360
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say <i>they give it to me</i>, <i>they give it to me</i>,

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:36.320
<v Teacher>in Spanish you would just say <i>they give me it</i>.

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:44.320
<v Teacher>The personal word <b>me</b> is going to come first and then <i>it</i> is going to come and the position where they go we know this already.

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.720
<v Teacher>So how would you say they give me it, they give it to me

00:01:50.159 --> 00:01:52.159
<v Student><b>Me lo dan</b>.

00:01:52.159 --> 00:01:52.719
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:01:52.719 --> 00:01:53.680
<v Teacher><b>Me lo dan</b>.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:56.799
<v Teacher>And now emphasize or clarify.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:59.520
<v Student><b>Ellos me lo dan</b>.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:00.960
<v Teacher><b>Ellos me lo dan</b>.

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:01.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.399
<v Teacher>Or <b>ellas</b> if they were female <i>they</i>.

00:02:04.399 --> 00:02:06.320
<v Teacher><b>Ellas me lo dan</b>.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:07.039
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:07.039 --> 00:02:09.759
<v Teacher>We said that with some future context

00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:12.320
<v Teacher>We don't need to use the future.

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:19.200
<v Teacher>So if you want to say I will give it to you tomorrow, you can just say I give it to you tomorrow.

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:20.720
<v Teacher>Let's talk informally.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.480
<v Teacher>So informally, how will you say I give you it tomorrow?

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:29.800
<v Student><b>Te lo doy mañana</b>.

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:31.480
<v Teacher><b>Te lo doy mañana</b>.

00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:36.980
<v Teacher>Very common, very Spanish sounding sentence. <b>Te lo doy mañana</b>, <i>I give you it tomorrow</i>,

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:40.500
<v Teacher>sounds strange in English but perfect Spanish. <b>Te lo doy mañana</b>.

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:43.500
<v Teacher>How would you say are you giving it to me tomorrow?

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:45.260
<v Teacher>And then speak formally.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:49.340
<v Teacher>So complicated sentence in English, are you giving it to me tomorrow?

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:52.540
<v Teacher>All we have to do in Spanish is just work out who's doing what

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:56.319
<v Teacher>We work out who's doing what and to who and we build that.

00:02:56.319 --> 00:02:57.680
<v Teacher>It's very simple in Spanish.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:00.560
<v Teacher>Complicated sentence in English but not in Spanish.

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:02.000
<v Teacher>Talking formally.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.720
<v Teacher>Are you giving it to me tomorrow?

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:07.280
<v Student>Well it's <b>da</b>.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:09.120
<v Teacher>That's the first thing you should work out, good.

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:12.720
<v Student>¿<b>Me lo da mañana</b>?

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:14.080
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:17.440
<v Teacher>Now what if we wanted to emphasize you?

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:18.160
<v Teacher>Are you

00:03:18.740 --> 00:03:22.020
<v Teacher>Giving it to me tomorrow.

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.140
<v Student>And <b>usted</b> can come in the beginning or the end?

00:03:25.140 --> 00:03:25.860
<v Teacher>Yeah.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:27.780
<v Student>So ¿<b>usted me lo da mañana</b>?

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:33.760
<v Teacher>¿<b>Usted me lo da mañana</b>? ¿<b>Me lo da usted mañana</b>? ¿<b>Me lo da mañana usted</b>?

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:38.800
<v Teacher>These words <b>usted</b>, <b>yo</b>, <b>él</b>, <b>ella</b> are extremely flexible for different emphasis.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:40.720
<v Teacher>Again, it's not something we want to

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:54.760
<v Teacher>teach here because that those nuances of emphasis change depending on the dialect and it's something that you pick up in real life because where people move it around is accompanied with a change in the voice and hand expressions and you understand

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:59.000
<v Teacher>in this case intuitively, which is emphatic.

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:02.440
<v Teacher><i>You guys</i> is <b>usted</b> but plural.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:07.720
<v Teacher>Now if the word ends in a consonant in Spanish, you don't just add –<i>s</i>, you add –<i>es</i>.

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:12.260
<v Teacher>So how would it sound, <i>you guys</i>?

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:13.380
<v Student><b>Ustedes</b>.

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:14.500
<v Teacher><b>Ustedes</b>.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:15.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:18.340
<v Teacher>So now let's say, will you guys give it

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:20.739
<v Teacher>To us tomorrow.

00:04:20.739 --> 00:04:27.300
<v Teacher>So again, we just want to work out who's doing and to who or to what are they doing, and then we can construct it.

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:31.220
<v Teacher>So are you guys giving it to us tomorrow

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:33.500
<v Student>So it's <b>dan</b>.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:34.380
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:37.180
<v Student>It's <b>nos</b> and it's still <b>lo</b>.

00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:38.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:41.660
<v Student>¿<b>Nos lo dan mañana</b>?

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:42.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:44.700
<v Teacher>Now this could mean you guys

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:48.340
<v Teacher>Or they give it to us tomorrow.

00:04:48.340 --> 00:04:51.940
<v Teacher>Now what if you wanted to clarify that it was <i>you guys</i>?

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:56.580
<v Student>¿<b>Ustedes nos lo dan mañana</b>?

00:04:56.580 --> 00:04:56.979
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:56.979 --> 00:05:03.460
<v Teacher>¿<b>Ustedes nos lo dan mañana</b>? ¿<b>Nos lo dan mañana ustedes</b>? ¿<b>Nos lo dan ustedes mañana</b>?

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:05.300
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I want to give</i>? <i>I want to give</i>:

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:07.780
<v Student><b>Quiero dar</b>.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:09.560
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:11.560
<v Teacher>I want to give you it.

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:13.320
<v Teacher>Talking informally.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.280
<v Teacher>Informally.

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:16.200
<v Teacher>I want to give it to you.

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:18.420
<v Student><b>Quiero das</b>.

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:20.020
<v Teacher>Work out the verbs first.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:21.460
<v Teacher><i>I want to give</i>, work that out first.

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:23.540
<v Student>Oh! <b>Quiero dar</b>.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.820
<v Teacher>Good, <i>to give you</i> is something else, it's not <i>you give</i>.

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:30.220
<v Teacher><i>I want to give</i>, <b>quiero dar</b>, <i>it to you</i>:

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:34.940
<v Student>So it's <b>lo</b> and it's <b>te</b>.

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:37.740
<v Teacher>Good. And in what order do they come?

00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:43.100
<v Student>It's <b>te lo quiero dar</b>.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:44.620
<v Teacher>Good.

